Here is a sample Java program that creates a button in a GUI using the AWT (Abstract Window Toolkit) library:
```
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class ButtonExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create a frame with a title and size
        Frame frame = new Frame("Button Example");
        frame.setSize(400, 300);
        frame.setLocationRelativeTo(null);

        // Create a button with a label and a listener
        Button button = new Button("Click me!");
        button.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                System.out.println("Button clicked");
            }
        });

        // Add the button to the frame
        frame.add(button);

        // Set the visibility of the frame and start it
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```
This program creates a `Frame` with a title "Button Example" and sets its size to 400x300 pixels. It then creates a `Button` with a label "Click me!" and adds an `ActionListener` that prints "Button clicked" to the console when the button is clicked. Finally, it sets the visibility of the frame to true and starts it.

You can use this program as a starting point for your own Java GUI applications. You can modify the code to suit your needs by adding or removing components, changing their properties, and adding event listeners.
